The code does not violate any SOLID principles as per the given context. However, it can be refactored to adhere more strictly to the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP) and Open-Closed Principle (OCP). 

In this case, we have a class `ReportGenerator` that is responsible for generating reports based on different types of sales data. This violates SRP as it has more than one reason to change - the ReportGenerator class can be changed in two ways: to generate new report types or to handle changes in how sales are represented (e.g., if Sale objects were to change).

To refactor this, we could separate the responsibility of generating reports into a different class that is only responsible for generating reports and another class that handles the specifics of what data to include in each type of report. This would adhere more closely to SRP and OCP:

```csharp
public interface IReportGenerator  {
    string Generate(SalesData sales);
}

public class DailyReport : IReportGenerator {
    public string Generate(SalesData data) {
        // Implementation for daily report...
    }
}

public class ProductReport : IReportGenerator {
    public string Generate(SalesData data) {
        // Implementation for product report...
    }
}
```

